---
/**
 * About Cedar — editorial explainer.
 *
 * The hero already shows Cedar in action (chatbot + map). This
 * section sits later in the page and answers a different question:
 * what Cedar actually IS, what it does on the real platforms, and
 * how data is handled. Three short transcript fragments make the
 * scope concrete without a second chat widget.
 */
import '../styles/cedar.css';
---
<section class="cedar-about" id="cedar">
  <div class="cedar-about__inner">
    <header class="cedar-about__head">
      <p class="cedar-about__eyebrow">Meet Cedar.</p>
      <h2 class="cedar-about__lead">
        An AI thought partner that <em>names the assumption</em><br>before the model ever runs on it.
      </h2>
      <p class="cedar-about__body">
        Cedar sits beside your work on every Lumecon platform &mdash; reading the messy uploads, asking the question the model is about to assume an answer to, and writing the ledger as you go. It won&rsquo;t think for you. It thinks with you.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="cedar-about__grid">
      <article class="cedar-card">
        <header class="cedar-card__head">
          <span class="cedar-card__num">i.</span>
          <h3 class="cedar-card__name">It reads what you upload.</h3>
        </header>
        <p class="cedar-card__desc">A spreadsheet, a budget PDF, a chapter audit. Cedar parses, asks where each line should land in the model, and flags anything ambiguous before a single multiplier touches it.</p>
        <div class="cedar-card__demo">
          <div class="cdemo cdemo--user"><span class="cdemo__from">You</span>Here&rsquo;s last quarter&rsquo;s payroll detail.</div>
          <div class="cdemo cdemo--cedar"><span class="cdemo__from">Cedar</span>Got it. Three of these rows are contractor payments, not employees. Want me to file them under indirect spend?</div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="cedar-card">
        <header class="cedar-card__head">
          <span class="cedar-card__num">ii.</span>
          <h3 class="cedar-card__name">It names every assumption.</h3>
        </header>
        <p class="cedar-card__desc">Before the run, Cedar surfaces what the model is about to assume &mdash; geography, supply-chain leakage, household propensity to consume &mdash; and asks you to confirm or override each one.</p>
        <div class="cedar-card__demo">
          <div class="cdemo cdemo--cedar"><span class="cdemo__from">Cedar</span>I&rsquo;ll model the supply chain as 38% in-region. Your call &mdash; the audit you ran last spring used 52%.</div>
          <div class="cdemo cdemo--user"><span class="cdemo__from">You</span>Use 52.</div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="cedar-card">
        <header class="cedar-card__head">
          <span class="cedar-card__num">iii.</span>
          <h3 class="cedar-card__name">It writes the ledger.</h3>
        </header>
        <p class="cedar-card__desc">Every run exports with the full assumption log: which sources, which vintages, every override you made, and a plain-language summary a reviewer can read without opening the spreadsheet.</p>
        <div class="cedar-card__demo">
          <div class="cdemo cdemo--cedar"><span class="cdemo__from">Cedar</span>Run complete. The ledger is at the top of your export &mdash; sources, vintages, overrides, and a one-paragraph summary your council can paste into the agenda.</div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>

    <footer class="cedar-about__foot">
      <p class="cedar-about__privacy">
        <span class="cedar-about__privacy-l">Privacy by default.</span>
        Cedar runs in a per-project sandbox. Provider calls are pseudonymized: project and file names are hashed before they leave the platform; your real user ID never appears upstream. The marketing-page Cedar you talked to above doesn&rsquo;t call out at all.
      </p>
      <a href="#contact" class="btn">Ask us anything about Cedar</a>
    </footer>
  </div>
</section>
